Dear \BEDITOR,

We are pleased to submit our manuscript entitled “\TITLE” for consideration as a regular paper  in \JNAME.

High-performance predictive models trained on large-scale EHR and biobank data have achieved remarkable discrimination for complex diseases. Yet attribution in these settings remains unreliable: despite excellent classification accuracy, classical odds ratios and post-hoc attribution methods such as SHAP often inflate weak associations and generate spuriously “protective” effects when applied to noisy diagnostic codes. This creates a paradox where models perform well at prediction but fail to yield trustworthy mechanistic insights.

In this work, we introduce the Lambda Odds Ratio ($\SPOR$), a misclassification-corrected measure of effect size that directly exploits the sensitivity–specificity tradeoffs encoded in a model’s ROC curve. $\SPOR$ collapses under non-informative predictors, resists amplification of vanishing effects, and remains stable under label noise. Applied to autism spectrum disorder, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, and Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias, $\SPOR$ suppresses inflated significance seen with odds ratios and SHAP while retaining biologically credible modulators.

Our findings provide a principled and practical framework for attribution in observational studies at biobank scale. By stabilizing inference against label noise while leveraging the operating characteristics of high-performing models, $\SPOR$ enables large-scale studies to move beyond spurious associations toward recovery of mechanistically consistent risk signals. We believe this work will be of broad interest to the readership of \JNAME, spanning epidemiology, biomedical informatics, and population genetics, and will contribute to the reliability of mechanistic discovery in population-scale data resources.

We thank you for your consideration.


